## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA support was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (or any DSA signing/verification) now **throws at runtime** on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch the signing algorithm. Your options:

1. **Verify on Linux/Windows only** — gate the DSA code path with a runtime check:
   ```csharp
   if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
       throw new PlatformNotSupportedException("DSA verification not supported on macOS in .NET 11+");
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** — e.g., [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography) provides a managed DSA implementation that works everywhere, independent of the OS:
   ```csharp
   // NuGet: BouncyCastle.Cryptography
   var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   verifier.Init(false, publicKey);
   verifier.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Migrate signatures to ECDSA/RSA** — if you control the signing side, re-sign with a modern algorithm and phase out DSA entirely.

For a library that must **verify existing DSA signatures on all platforms**, option 2 (BouncyCastle) is the most practical path forward.
